{{infobox Onsen | Name = Masutomi Onsen (増富温泉) | image = {{画像募集中|cat=北杜市}} | Comment = | Location = [[:en:Yamanashi Prefecture|Yamanashi Prefecture]] [[:en:Hokuto, Yamanashi|Hokuto City]] Sutama Town, Hishi (須玉町比志) | Access = Rail: Approximately 60 minutes by bus from the [[:en:Chūō Main Line|Chuo Main Line]] at [[:en:Nirasaki Station|Nirasaki Station]] via [[:en:Yamanashi Kōtsū|Yamanashi Kotsu]] | Spring Quality = {{ill|Radioactive Hot Spring|ja|放射能泉|1=Radioactive spring|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Radioactive Hot Spring|qq=}} | Spring Temperature = | Flow Rate = | pH = | Classification of Liquid Nature = | Classification of Osmotic Pressure = | Number of Lodging Facilities = | Total Capacity = | Annual Number of Bathers = | Statistical Year = | External Links = | Special Notes = }}
'''Masutomi Onsen''' (ますとみおんせん), also known as '''Masutomi Radium Onsen''', is a hot spring located in [[:en:Yamanashi Prefecture|Yamanashi Prefecture]], [[:en:Hokuto, Yamanashi|Hokuto City]], Sutama Town Hishi.
== Spring Quality == * {{ill|Radioactive Hot Spring|ja|放射能泉|1=Radioactive spring|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Radioactive Hot Spring|qq=}} ** It has an extremely high radium content; there are records indicating that the radium content reaches as high as 12,300 [[マッヘ]] per liter. ** The source water temperature is about 30°C, making it a lukewarm spring. A longer soaking time of 15 to 30 minutes is generally recommended. * Hot Spring Overview (based on data for “Masutomi no Yu”) ** The source water is classified as a carbon dioxide–containing, sodium, chloride, and bicarbonate hot spring (a hypertonic, neutral, low-temperature spring). * Efficacy ** Beneficial for conditions such as diabetes, gout, muscle fatigue, mental fatigue, circulatory disorders, rheumatism, allergic predispositions, visceral fatigue, atopic dermatitis, menopausal disorders, liver dysfunction, and cholelithiasis, among others.
== Hot Spring Town == Located within the [[:en:Chichibu Tama Kai National Park|Chichibu Tama Kai National Park]], the erosion by the Honya River—a tributary of the {{ill|Shio River (Yamanashi)|ja|塩川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shio River (Yamanashi)|qq=}}—has carved out a valley where eight traditional [[:en:Ryokan|ryokan]] are nestled in the mountains. There is no communal bath; however, one day-use bathing facility called “Masutomi no Yu” operated by the general incorporated association "Gochi no Sato Tamayura" existed. Due to aging facilities and the need for inspections, it has been temporarily closed since April 1, 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.masutominoyu.com/article.php?id=15 |title=「増富の湯」４月から休業のお知らせ|date=2023-03-10 |accessdate=2023-12-14}}</ref> == History == [[File:Kyoshi Takahama.jpg|thumb|200px|[[:en:Kyoshi Takahama|Takahama Kyoshi]]]] The name “Masutomi” derives from Masutomi Village, which existed from 1875 (Meiji 8) to 1959 (Showa 34). According to legend, it is a hidden hot spring discovered by {{ill|Takeda Shingen|ja|Takeda Shingen|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takeda Shingen|qq=}} during the development of a gold mine. Owing to its excellent efficacy, it flourished as a therapeutic bathing site. Situated in a scenic area with views of {{ill|Konpōzan|ja|金峰山|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Konpōzan|qq=}} (in Yamanashi and Nagano) and [[:en:Mount Mizugaki|Zuiheizan]], in modern times many literati and artists—including [[:en:Kyoshi Takahama|Takahama Kyoshi]], [[:en:Masuji Ibuse|Ibusuki Masuji]], [[:en:Gishū Nakayama|Nakayama Yoshihide]], and {{ill|Tanaka Fuyuji|ja|田中冬二|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tanaka Fuyuji|qq=}}—visited Masutomi Onsen. On August 5, 1965 (Showa 40), it was designated as a {{ill|National Public Resort Hot Spring Area|ja|国民保養温泉地|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/National Public Resort Hot Spring Area|qq=}}. In 2004, during the Onsen Adulterat